Thats because in order to have a healthy relationship between a feline and a human each of them will need to learn how to more effectively communicate with each other nonverbally.

Most felines have very subtle forms of nonverbally communicating affection, frustration, anger, and joy that a human may not be able to readily pick up on without both guidance and time. A human will need to learn their partners body language in order to be able to effectively understand their mood.

And the reverse is true as felines can often find themselves frustrated trying to better express and understand verbally communicating issues with their partner instead of relying on their instinctual knowledge.

If they are unable to do this both parties may end up feeling stonewalled by the other as communication breaks down. But ironically this whole time they ARE talking to each other, but not understanding one another.

Like >>60044650 said forming a healthy relationship takes time and being able to understand the very subtle nonverbal communication essential to felines

Anonymous Thu 05 Oct 2023 03:50:03 No.60066855 Report
Quoted By: >>60066891 >>60067047
>>60066184
Yeah. This. One of the things you learn from playing with it, that isn't always necessarily really obvious from just looking at pictures and reading prompts, is that if you stack too many lora files together at high strengths you get a dark, muddy, grainy "deep fried" image with chromatic aberration, and maybe out of focus too. And you can put "chromatic aberration" and all the rest of that in the negative prompt but the images will usually still come out looking like a still from some art-house "found footage" horror movie, dark and muddy with melted eyes.

One lora file can be used at 1.0, maybe, but if you're using two or three, the main one you want to emphasize probably shouldn't be over 0.75, and the others at 0.25, maybe, if that. Even then you can still get things like this, just not quite so often.
